entry.title: Fix use after free in XRWebGLLayer
entry.content:
When the antialias attribute is called on an inline session it echoes

the antialias value of the WebGL context's drawing buffer. If the WebGL

context has been lost, however, the drawing buffer is null.



This change checks to see if the context is lost before accessing the

drawing buffer. If so it returns false. This is a reasonable value

according to the spec, which states the attribute should return "false

if no antialiasing will be performed."



Bug: 1503503

entry.title: Fix the broken tests when AppStorage is enabled(Part 14).
entry.content:
When the kAppServiceStorage flag is enabled, AppService blocks the

app publishers creating until it's ready, after reading from the

AppStorage file, e.g. BrowserCommandControllerFullscreenTest.*.



Because the web app publisher is created async by AppServiceProxy

during the test shutdown stage. the web app provider doesn't exist.

This causes the CHECK error.



Modify the web app publisher to check whether the web app provider is

available during the web app publisher init stage.

no regressions in the desired behavior of the policy w.r.t. default

search provider not set by policy and starter pack.



A summary of the tests added:

- For non-featured site search (keyword not starting with "@"):

- Do not override user-defined DSP

- Do not override DSP set by extension

- Override pre-defined DSP if the user has not modified it

- For featured site search:

- Override user-defined DSP for keyword search

- Override DSP set by extension for keyword search

- Override starter pack



Even though we may override DSP for keyword search, the site search

policy doesn't change the DSP, so the user can still access it in the

Omnibox by simply using no keyword.

entry.title: Remove existing uses of the default constructor of `reporting::StatusOr`
entry.content:
As a cautious measure, because existing code may have assumed that the

default constructor creates an error status, but the current behavior

(after migrating to `base::expected`) is a default correct value.



In the future, the default constructor is still allowed to be used, with

the knowledge that the default constructor constructs a default correct

value, not an error status.



This mirrors the effort in crrev.com/c/5132907.



The detection of the uses of this constructor is helped by the following

patch:



diff --git a/base/types/expected.h b/base/types/expected.h

index 00ec66517780..ff454ccbd57a 100644

--- a/base/types/expected.h

+++ b/base/types/expected.h

@@ -15,6 +15,10 @@

#include "base/types/expected_internal.h" // IWYU pragma: export

#include "third_party/abseil-cpp/absl/utility/utility.h"



+namespace reporting::internal {

+ class ErrorStatus;

+}

+

// Class template `expected` is a vocabulary type which contains an

// expected value of type `T`, or an error `E`. The class skews towards behaving

// like a `T`, because its intended use is when the expected type is contained.

@@ -289,6 +293,9 @@ class [[nodiscard]] expected final {

// [expected.object.ctor], constructors

constexpr expected() noexcept = default;



+ expected() noexcept

+ requires(std::is_same_v) = delete;

+

// Converting copy and move constructors. These constructors are explicit if

// either the value or error type is not implicitly convertible from `rhs`'s

// corresponding type.

entry.title: [PriceDrop] Support skipping delayed init for ShoppingPersistedTabData
entry.content:
Currently on startup, ShoppingPersistedTabData are initialized in a

delayed style and won't be ready until onDeferredStartup is called.

This is to minimize the performance impact that the initialization

have on startup. However, this would mean that the data could be ready

too late if the very first page after startup is NTP and we try to

render the price change module.



To deal with this issue, we add a new method in this CL to skip

the delayed init and init immediately for tabs that might have

price drops. This could potentially regress startup performance,

however, we'll experiment this approach considering that (1) having

data ready for the very first NTP after startup is very important for

the feature (2) the number of tabs that might have price drop should

be small. Also, we guard this new code path behind a Finch parameter,

so that we can disable it anytime if we need to.



This CL is the implementation of this part in the design doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1eUYWgGn5VbemTYgSsD6mLU_3DS8xZvDR8_60HYKY6XY/edit?tab=t.0#bookmark=id.8r4uwrg0t2l4.

entry.title: [WebAuthn] Allow credentials.create() in a cross-origin iframe
entry.content:
As of https://github.com/w3c/webauthn/pull/1801, the WebAuthn spec

allows for credential creation in a cross-origin iframe, as long as

the "publickey-credentials-create" permission policy is set AND

there is a user activation for the call. Previously, Chrome supported

this but only for 'payment' WebAuthn credentials*, which also used

a different permission policy ("payment").



This CL updates Chrome to support calling credentials.create() for

a publickey in a cross-origin iframe, as long as the above conditions

are met. The behavior is behind a runtime-enabled flag,

WebAuthnAllowCreateInCrossOriginFrame, which is currently set to

"experimental". It will be set to stable once we have an approved

I2S for this feature.



This CL does NOT update the behavior for "payment" extension

credentials, which still require the "payment" permission policy

for now. crbug.com/1512605 and crbug.com/1512245 track the

required changes there.



* That is, credential creation calls in which the payment extension

is specified.

entry.title: [Extensions] Refactor service worker test event dispatch test.
entry.content:
This refactoring enhances the test by additionally using a

content::ServiceWorkerVersion::Observer instead of just a

content::ServiceWorkerContextObserver.



Before this change it wasn't guaranteed that events were dispatched at

the blink::EmbeddedWorkerStatus meant for the test because

content::ServiceWorkerContextObserver observers are notified

asynchronously of worker status changes.



After this change all tests will now synchronously dispatch their test

events immediately when the worker status is in the state they want to

test.



This requires some bleed between //extensions and

//content/browser/service_worker/ but it is inevitable since we need to

know the internal running status of the worker. It has been approved by

the Chrome Worker team.

entry.title: Add a CPUProportionTracker helper class
entry.content:
This moves the code from PageTimelineCPUMonitor that converts a

CPUTimeResult to a proportion of a fixed interval into a helper that can

be used by other classes.



Also fixes some missed cases that were found while adding unit tests:



* Ignores contexts that have no CPUTimeResult instead of crashing.

(PageTimelineCPUMonitor always has a CPUTimeResult but future callers

may not.)

* Excludes contexts whose CPU usage was entirely before the current

interval from the result, instead of including them with a CPU of

0%. (Optimization only. This doesn't affect PageTimelineCPUMonitor

since it always checks if the PageNode for a PageContext still exists

before logging any metrics.)

* Excludes contexts with CPU usage before the current interval if it's

not possible to know how much of the CPU was before the interval. The

code in PageTimelineCPUMonitor incorrectly included all the context's

CPU in this case.



R=agale
